<h1 local-id=3D"143f7f5f868a" id=3D"Task20-Technicaldocument-11.ContinuousI=
mprovement">11. Continuous Improvement</h1>
<h2 local-id=3D"61b802d233a5" id=3D"Task20-Technicaldocument-11.1Feedbackan=
dRetrospectives">11.1 Feedback and Retrospectives</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"7f516424bf22">Post-implementation retrospective identified t=
he glue A record as the most commonly missed and misunderstood step =E2=80=
=94 this is now called out explicitly as CRITICAL in the zone file configur=
ation section of this document and all future DNS runbooks</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"98cfdb83819d">The IPv6 UDP setup failed warnings in dig +tra=
ce output caused initial confusion during validation =E2=80=94 documented a=
s expected and non-critical behavior for EC2 instances without IPv6 enabled=
, to prevent future false-alarm incidents</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"74cf8cd6ef3b">The team noted that lowering the TTL from 6048=
00 (7 days) to 300 (5 minutes) during initial setup and testing significant=
ly reduces the time needed to observe propagation effects =E2=80=94 this is=
 now the default recommended TTL for all new zone configurations during eva=
luation phases</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"3a72a57d8f0a">dig +trace is now established as the mandatory=
 final validation step for all DNS configuration changes, replacing simple =
dig queries as the single acceptance test</p></li>
</ul>
<h2 local-id=3D"dbca76544103" id=3D"Task20-Technicaldocument-11.2IterativeE=
nhancements">11.2 Iterative Enhancements</h2>
<p local-id=3D"4e9145ecc7a5">The following improvements are planned for sub=
sequent iterations of this DNS implementation:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"350b6b81d647"><strong>Secondary BIND9 Server:</strong> Add a=
 second EC2 instance configured as a BIND9 slave with zone transfer from th=
e primary =E2=80=94 eliminating the current single point of failure in the =
self-hosted DNS environment</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"db5655823b44"><strong>DNSSEC Implementation:</strong> Sign t=
he BIND9 zone with DNSSEC to provide cryptographic validation of DNS respon=
ses =E2=80=94 protecting against DNS cache poisoning and man-in-the-middle =
spoofing attacks</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"49bcb4b516d2"><strong>Automation with Ansible:</strong> Deve=
lop an Ansible playbook to automate the full BIND9 provisioning workflow =
=E2=80=94 apt install, named.conf configuration, zone file deployment, Secu=
rity Group rule application, and service restart =E2=80=94 enabling repeata=
ble, one-command DNS server provisioning</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"176a2f7bbadc"><strong>Infrastructure as Code:</strong> Terra=
form module to provision the EC2 instance, Security Group, and Route 53 NS/=
glue records in a single deployment =E2=80=94 replacing manual console-base=
d configuration</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"bf46c537a01c"><strong>Monitoring Integration:</strong> Cloud=
Watch agent on BIND9 EC2 to ship named query logs; synthetic dig health che=
ck cron job; CloudWatch alarm on health check failure =E2=86=92 SNS notific=
ation</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"22f24add5262"><strong>Production Migration to Route 53:</str=
ong> For all production DNS workloads, migrate zones from BIND9 to Route 53=
 to leverage the Anycast network, 100% SLA, and zero operational overhead =
=E2=80=94 retaining BIND9 only for hybrid or on-premises DNS use cases</p><=
/li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h1 local-id=3D"bf86404e671c" id=3D"Task20-Technicaldocument-12.Conclusion"=
>12. Conclusion</h1>
<h2 local-id=3D"87e15ca68c1b" id=3D"Task20-Technicaldocument-12.1Summary">1=
2.1 Summary</h2>
<p local-id=3D"a2661f61b9c7">This document has described the complete imple=
mentation of a self-hosted BIND9 DNS server on AWS EC2 and its integration =
with AWS Route 53 through NS record delegation. The key outcomes achieved a=
re:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"aee621347f4d"><strong>Self-Hosted DNS Operational:</strong> =
BIND9 installed and configured on EC2 (ubuntu@ip-172-31-92-210, 54.161.204.=
194) as the authoritative nameserver for lab.karna.pushkar.cloud, serving A=
 and NS records from a custom zone file</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"6d1e4df1df29"><strong>NS Delegation Configured:</strong> Rou=
te 53 hosted zone (karna.pushkar.cloud) successfully delegates the lab subd=
omain to the EC2 BIND9 server via NS record and glue A record =E2=80=94 cre=
ating a fully functional DNS chain</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"8b685fbdb6bc"><strong>Full 5-Hop Resolution Chain Validated:=
</strong> dig +trace confirmed the complete resolution path from Root Serve=
rs =E2=86=92 .cloud TLD =E2=86=92 pushkar.cloud (Route 53) =E2=86=92 karna.=
pushkar.cloud (Route 53) =E2=86=92 BIND9 EC2 =E2=80=94 with the final autho=
ritative answer served by the self-hosted DNS server at 54.161.204.194 in 0=
ms response time</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"9c767d9c5406"><strong>DNS Concepts Demonstrated:</strong> Th=
e exercise practically illustrated SOA records, NS delegation, glue records=
, TTL behavior, DNS propagation, IPv6 fallback, and the difference between =
iterative resolver behavior and authoritative responses</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"d8d9681b997e"><strong>Route 53 vs Self-Hosted Comparison:</s=
trong> Route 53 provides a 12x cost advantage ($0.90/month vs $10.67/month)=
, global Anycast performance, a 100% SLA, and zero operational overhead =E2=
=80=94 it is the clear recommendation for all production DNS workloads. BIN=
D9 remains valuable as a learning tool and for on-premises or hybrid DNS sc=
enarios</p></li>
</ul>
<h2 local-id=3D"20fec4cfbcce" id=3D"Task20-Technicaldocument-12.2NextSteps"=
>12.2 Next Steps</h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"86fc3acb4610">Implement DNSSEC signing on the BIND9 zone for=
 cryptographic DNS validation</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"2546a60ce4cc">Add a secondary BIND9 EC2 instance with zone t=
ransfer to eliminate the single-point-of-failure</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"860d0ba10b9c">Migrate all production DNS zones to Route 53 a=
nd decommission the BIND9 EC2 to realise cost savings</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"e441a0537411">Automate BIND9 provisioning with Ansible and m=
anage zone files as code in GitHub with CI validation</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"80a769b08e76">Configure CloudWatch synthetic monitoring for =
continuous DNS health validation post-implementation</p></li>
<li>
<p local-id=3D"ff0dc8966c08">Explore AWS Route 53 Resolver for internal VPC=
 DNS to fully eliminate any remaining EC2-based DNS dependency</p></li>
